  {
    "cname": "Swimming anemone, see comment",
    "sname": "",
    "Portrait": "0",
    "show": "1",
    "Mute": "1",
    "cell": "3b",
    "fit": "fc",
    "link": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-6lMD9h_ix4",
    "attribution": "",
    "comment": "Only a very small number of sea anemones are known to actively “swim” in the sense of repeatedly contracting their body or tentacles to move away from predators like sea stars, and the list is not completely settled, but the behavior has been clearly documented in just a few species.  Based on published descriptions and expert summaries, the sea anemones that have been observed to perform true, active swimming or vigorous escape movements comparable to Stomphia coccinea are:  Stomphia coccinea – The classic example; it detaches from the substrate and flexes its column in strong undulations to swim away from predatory sea stars such as Dermasterias imbricata.  Stomphia didemon (often called the “swimming anemone”) – Closely related to S. coccinea; when contacted by a predatory sea star (e.g., Dermasterias imbricata), it first attacks with its tentacles and then performs a prolonged escape “swim” by bending back and forth and bouncing along, moved by currents. ​  Gonactinia prolifera – Reported as unusual in that it can both walk and swim; swimming is achieved by rapid, synchronous tentacle movements that act like oar strokes, propelling the animal through the water. ​  “Sea onion” anemone (a common name used for a burrowing anemone species) – Not a strong swimmer like Stomphia, but it can inflate, detach, adopt a roughly spherical shape, and let waves and currents roll it away; this is a locomotory escape response, though more passive than active swimming. ​  Many other anemones can slowly creep, detach, or drift, but as far as currently documented behavior goes, only these few have been specifically described in the literature and expert summaries as exhibiting active, coordinated swimming or vigorous escape movements analogous to Stomphia coccinea when fleeing stars.",
